By taking inspiration from the favorable merits, CQDs have been extensively used in many fields, such as electrochemical energy conversion and storage, photocatalysis, and biosensors. In order to obtain high-quality CQDs, numerous efforts have been devoted to the rational fabrication of CQDs, and many efficient strategies have been successfully developed. As illustrated in Scheme 1
                     , depending on the carbon source utilized, the synthesis of CQDs can be clearly categorized into two methods: top-down and bottom-up approaches, both of which are effective for the synthesis of high-quality CQDs. In the following section, we would provide a detailed discussion and a comparison (Table 1
                     ) of the top-down and bottom-up approaches for the synthesis of CQDs.

In addition to the detection of caffeic acid, the optical nanosensor based on GQDs is also highly efficient for the determination of other substance, such as amino acid. For example, Wang et al. have successfully fabricated a nanosensor that is constructed by coupling Au nanoparticles with GQDs and graphene-like carbon nitride (g-C3N4) [100]. Significantly, the g-C3N4 is working as the photoactive material, GQDs are serving as the photoactivity improvement reagent, while Au nanoparticles are the immobilization substrate for DNA probe (Fig. 9
                        ). Interestingly, the DNA biotin labeled aptamer could function as the zeatin recognition and streptavidin capture element, while the streptavidin can act as the PEC response inhibitor factor. The PEC detection mechanisms are illustrated as follows: in the presence of zeatin, DNA aptamer could effectively bind with zeatin to generate conjugate, making aptamer releasing from electrode surface to dramatically decrease the capture amount of streptavidin, which will inevitably cause the enhancement of the PEC signal. As a result, this biosensor could exhibit a wide linear range of 0.1−100 nm, together with ultralow low detection limit of 0.031 nm. Moreover, a comparison of the sensors based on CQDs for the application in the food safety has also been listed in the Table 2
                        .
